      "title": "Spice Girls",
      "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/ac/Spice_Girls_in_Toronto%2C_Ontario.jpg",
      "body": '''
The **Spice Girls** are a British girl group formed in 1994, consisting of [Melanie Brown](openitem:mel-b) - [wiki:Melanie Brown](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mel_B "Mel B"), also known as Mel B ("Scary Spice"); [Melanie Chisholm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanie_C "Melanie C"), or Melanie C ("Sporty Spice"); [Emma Bunton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emma_Bunton "Emma Bunton") ("Baby Spice"); [Geri Halliwell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geri_Halliwell "Geri Halliwell") ("Ginger Spice"); and [Victoria Beckham](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victoria_Beckham "Victoria Beckham") ("Posh Spice"). With their "[girl power](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girl_power "Girl power")" mantra, they redefined the girl-group concept by targeting a young female fanbase.[\[1\]](#cite_note-johnharlow-1)[\[2\]](#cite_note-andrewsmith-2) They led the [teen pop](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teen_pop "Teen pop") resurgence of the 1990s, were a major part of the [Cool Britannia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cool_Britannia "Cool Britannia") era, and became pop culture icons of the decade.[\[3\]](#cite_note-Time_magazine-3)[\[4\]](#cite_note-sherrie-4)[\[5\]](#cite_note-spice_girls_bio-5)

The group formed through auditions held by managers [Bob](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Herbert_(manager) "Bob Herbert (manager)") and [Chris Herbert](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Herbert "Chris Herbert"), who wanted to create a girl group to compete with the British [boy bands](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boy_band "Boy band") popular at the time. They signed to [Virgin Records](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virgin_Records "Virgin Records") and released their debut single "[Wannabe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wannabe "Wannabe")" in 1996, which reached number one on the charts of 37 countries.[\[6\]](#cite_note-bbc37-6)[\[7\]](#cite_note-Billboardwann-7) Their debut album, _[Spice](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spice_(album) "Spice (album)")_ (1996), sold more than 23 million copies worldwide, becoming [the best-selling album by a female group in history](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_best-selling_girl_groups#Best-selling_girl_group_albums "List of best-selling girl groups").[\[8\]](#cite_note-US_sales-8) The follow-up, _[Spiceworld](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiceworld_(album) "Spiceworld (album)")_ (1997), sold more than 14 million copies worldwide.[\[9\]](#cite_note-spiceworldsales-9) Both albums encapsulated the group's [dance-pop](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dance-pop "Dance-pop") style and message of female empowerment, with vocal and songwriting contributions shared equally by the members. In 1997, a film starring the Spice Girls, _[Spice World](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spice_World_(film) "Spice World (film)"),_ was released; it was a commercial success but received poor reviews.

In May 1998, Halliwell left the Spice Girls, citing exhaustion and creative differences. The group carried on as a four-piece with the 1998 [Spiceworld Tour](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiceworld_Tour "Spiceworld Tour"), which was attended by an estimated 2.1 million people to become the highest-grossing concert tour by a female group.[\[10\]](#cite_note-bbcatoz-10) _[Forever](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forever_(Spice_Girls_album) "Forever (Spice Girls album)")_ (2000), the only Spice Girls album without Halliwell, achieved weaker sales.[\[11\]](#cite_note-simth206-11) At the end of 2000, the Spice Girls entered a hiatus to concentrate on their solo careers. They reunited for two concert tours, [the Return of the Spice Girls](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Return_of_the_Spice_Girls_Tour "The Return of the Spice Girls Tour") (2007–2008) and [Spice World](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spice_World_%E2%80%93_2019_Tour "Spice World – 2019 Tour") (2019), both of which won the [_Billboard_ Live Music Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billboard_Live_Music_Awards "Billboard Live Music Awards") for highest-grossing engagements, making them the top touring all-female group from 2000 to 2020.[\[12\]](#cite_note-pollstar-12) _[Viva Forever!](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viva_Forever!_(musical) "Viva Forever! (musical)")_, a musical based on the Spice Girls' music, opened in 2012; it was a critical and commercial failure and closed in 2013.

More at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spice_Girls 
''',
