A **battery electric vehicle** (**BEV**), **pure electric vehicle**, **only-electric vehicle**, **fully electric vehicle** or **all-electric vehicle** is a type of [electric vehicle](/wiki/Electric_vehicle "Electric vehicle") (EV) that exclusively uses [chemical energy](/wiki/Chemical_energy "Chemical energy") stored in [rechargeable battery](/wiki/Rechargeable_battery "Rechargeable battery") [packs](/wiki/Battery_pack "Battery pack"), with no secondary source of propulsion (e.g. hydrogen fuel cell, internal combustion engine, etc.). BEVs use [electric motors](/wiki/Electric_motor "Electric motor") and [motor controllers](/wiki/Motor_controller "Motor controller") instead of [internal combustion engines](/wiki/Internal_combustion_engine "Internal combustion engine") (ICEs) for propulsion. They derive all power from battery packs and thus have no internal combustion engine, [fuel cell](/wiki/Fuel_cell "Fuel cell"), or [fuel tank](/wiki/Fuel_tank "Fuel tank"). BEVs include – but are not limited to[\[1\]](#cite_note-1)[\[2\]](#cite_note-2) – motorcycles, bicycles, scooters, skateboards, railcars, watercraft, forklifts, buses, trucks, and cars.

In 2016, there were 210 million electric bikes worldwide used daily.[\[3\]](#cite_note-3) Cumulative global sales of highway-capable light-duty pure electric car vehicles passed the one million unit milestone in September 2016.[\[4\]](#cite_note-1miBEVs-4) As of October 2020[\[update\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Battery_electric_vehicle&action=edit), the world's top selling all-electric car in history is the [Tesla Model 3](/wiki/Tesla_Model_3 "Tesla Model 3"), with an estimated 645,000 sales,[\[5\]](#cite_note-5) followed by the [Nissan Leaf](/wiki/Nissan_Leaf "Nissan Leaf") with over 500,000 sales as of September 2020[\[update\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Battery_electric_vehicle&action=edit).[\[6\]](#cite_note-6)

See more https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battery_electric_vehicle
